          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819908?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名员工在巴格达的货币兑换处清点钞票。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：murtaja Lateef/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066658"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/david-s-cloud" itemprop="url" rel="author">大卫·S·克劳德</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 19 日下午 6:05（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-sanctions-14-iraqi-banks-in-crackdown-on-iran-dollar-trade-33ef9f35"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>华盛顿——美国官员表示，美国已禁止 14 家伊拉克银行进行美元交易，这是全面<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iraqis-fly-to-nearby-countries-to-get-dollars-as-u-s-cracks-down-on-money-laundering-ec366494?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">打击美元流入伊朗和其他受制裁中东国家的行动</a>的一部分。</p><p>美国财政部和纽约联邦储备银行周三实施的这项禁令可能会引发巴格达和华盛顿之间新的紧张关系，并可能<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iraq-economy-reels-as-u-s-moves-against-money-flows-to-iran-11674128633?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">给普通伊拉克人引发更多经济动荡</a>。</p><p>这标志着在拜登政府<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-launches-quiet-diplomatic-push-with-iran-to-cool-tensions-2f45af3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">似乎有意缓和与德黑兰的紧张关系</a>几个月后，美国加强了对伊朗的制裁。美国财政部最近批准支付25亿欧元（约合28亿美元），用于支付伊拉克政府因伊朗电力和天然气进口而未偿还的债务，这些债务因制裁而被冻结。</p><p>本周早些时候，五角大楼向该地区派遣了一艘军舰和喷气式战斗机，称这是为了回应伊朗对波斯湾商业航运的威胁。</p><p>美国官员表示，在发现伊拉克银行从事洗钱和欺诈交易的信息后，他们正在对这些银行采取行动，其中一些交易可能涉及受制裁的个人，并引发了伊朗可能受益的担忧。</p><p>美国官员表示，美元限制的主要目标是遏制伊拉克的洗钱活动。</p><p>一位美国高级官员表示：“我们有充分的理由怀疑，至少其中一些洗钱资金最终可能会惠及被指定的个人或可能被指定的个人。”他补充道，“当然，伊拉克的主要制裁风险与伊朗。”</p><p>即使按照伊拉克的标准，美国针对的大多数银行都是小型机构。两名伊拉克银行业专家表示，其中一些人与有影响力的伊拉克人有联系，因与伊朗有金融联系或大量参与美元交易而闻名。</p><p>美国名单上的银行包括穆斯塔沙尔伊斯兰银行、埃尔比勒银行、世界伊斯兰银行和扎因伊拉克伊斯兰银行。埃尔比勒银行董事长穆罕默德·赛义德·巴尔赞吉在电子邮件评论中表示，他尚未收到有关美元禁令的通知，并表示该银行的交易都经过仔细检查，以防止欺诈。其他银行没有回复寻求对美国行动发表评论的消息。伊拉克中央银行发言人也没有回应置评请求。</p><p>周三晚上，在另一家目标银行塔伊夫伊斯兰银行的巴格达分行，几名排队的顾客正在寻求购买美元用于海外旅行，或者正在接收来自国外的美元汇款。一位不愿透露姓名的出纳员表示：“一切都很正常，人们正常收款和汇款。”</p><p>伊朗长期以来一直利用邻国伊拉克作为因美国制裁而无法获得硬通货的来源，利用其与许多伊拉克政界人士的密切联系以及在伊拉克监管宽松的货币市场上容易获得美元的优势。</p><p>自 2003 年美国入侵伊拉克以来，美元大量涌入伊拉克，美元实际上已成为伊拉克的第二官方货币。二十年后，伊拉克仍然将其外汇储备存放在纽约联储，将其石油销售收入存入那里的官方账户。</p><p>据现任和前任美国和伊拉克官员称，伊拉克银行和货币兑换所想出了如何通过欺诈性进口交易和其他计划从美元中赚取巨额利润。以固定利率从央行购买的美元可以以通常大幅上涨的市场利率转售。</p><p>美国官员和伊拉克银行家表示，阻止获得美元对许多伊拉克银行来说无异于慢性死刑，这些银行的存款人很少，商业贷款也很少，大部分利润依赖美元交易。二十年来，伊拉克美元贸易已成为其普遍腐败的根源，因为银行家与伊拉克强大的民兵和政客结成联盟，以确保获得美元。</p><p>去年11月，当财政部和伊拉克中央银行切断其他四家银行获取美元的渠道并对电汇实施更严格的控制时，伊拉克第纳尔兑美元汇率暴跌，进口商品价格飙升，导致伊拉克第纳尔兑美元汇率暴跌，导致伊拉克第纳尔兑美元汇率暴跌，进口商品价格飙升，导致伊拉克第纳尔兑美元汇率暴跌，进口商品价格飙升，导致伊拉克第纳尔兑美元汇率暴跌，进口商品价格飙升，导致伊拉克第纳尔兑美元汇率暴跌，进口商品价格飙升，导致伊拉克第纳尔兑美元汇率暴跌。伊拉克总理穆罕默德·苏达尼面临一个月的危机。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819910?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">伊拉克第纳尔兑美元贬值引发伊拉克民众抗议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ahmad al-rubaye/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这些措施导致通过伊拉克商业银行的每日美元转账（有时每天总额超过 2.5 亿美元）下降了 80% 或更多，因为贷款机构难以遵守提供有关资金去向的详细信息的要求。</p><p>官员们表示，自去年以来对美元交易进行更严格的审查有助于美联储识别出进行可疑交易的 14 家银行。</p><p>另一位美国官员表示，近几个月来，几家银行已停止进行电汇，显然无法向美联储提供足够的信息来批准该交易。</p><p>这位高级官员表示，一些人采用了非法转移美元的新计划，包括将交易转移到不同的银行，以期逃避美联储的审查。他补充说，其他人尝试在伊拉克使用大量载有第纳尔的现金卡，然后运往附近国家，在那里可以以美元提取资金。</p><p>他说，为了逃避审查，一些银行还扩大了对西方汇款公司和中东非正式网络（称为“哈瓦拉”）的现金转移的使用。</p><p>官员们淡化了美国最新举措对伊拉克经济的影响，援引内部统计数据显示，14家银行合计仅持有伊拉克银行业总资产的1.29%。他们补充说，伊拉克的大部分合法银行活动都是由国有银行进行的，该国还有另外 46 家商业银行未受到美元禁令的影响。</p><p>此举的影响之一可能是推升伊拉克非官方汇率，自今年早些时候达到1,620伊拉克第纳尔兑1美元以来，该汇率已跌至1,470第纳尔兑1美元。美国官员表示，他们预计任何增加都是暂时的。</p><p>官员们表示，自去年秋天美国财政部和纽约联储开始更严格地审查美元活动以来，通过伊拉克外汇系统进行的欺诈交易数量已经减少，这将减轻禁止更多银行的经济影响。</p><p>这位高级官员表示：“由于存在更多的真实贸易，而不是本质上基于贸易的洗钱活动，因此我们预计活动的下降幅度要小得多。”</p><p>苏丹尼表示，自去年秋天以来，美国和伊拉克当局对美元流动进行了更严格的审查，导致了经济动荡。但伊拉克总理承认伊拉克银行的弱点，并将阻止欺诈交易归功于对美元交易的更严格限制。</p><p> “不幸的是，我们没有银行系统，无论是政府的还是私人的，这是一个真正的问题，”苏丹尼在中东研究所五月份在巴格达举办的政策会议伊拉克论坛上发表讲话时说。 “这是一个洗钱过程、走私货币以及使用虚假文件进行的虚假交易。”</p><p>多年来，美国官员一直向伊拉克施压，要求其加强银行业控制。官员们当时表示，2015年，美联储和财政部短暂切断了美元向伊拉克央行的流动，因为担心美元最终流入伊朗银行并可能流入伊斯兰国武装分子手中。</p><p>但历届美国政府担心，完全切断巴格达获得美元的渠道将使该国陷入经济动荡，危及其他目标，例如防止伊斯兰国重新出现以及将巴格达从德黑兰赶走。但美国官员表示，他们希望巴格达开始采取更多措施打击银行系统的洗钱和欺诈行为。</p><p> “我们希望伊拉克采取更积极主动的行动，因为我们不希望只是不断地打地鼠，”这位高级官员说。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——巴格达的加桑·阿德南 (Ghassan Adnan) 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 David S. Cloud： <a href="mailto:david.cloud@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">david.cloud@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 22:05:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-sanctions-14-iraqi-banks-in-crackdown-on-iran-dollar-trade-33ef9f35</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-sanctions-14-iraqi-banks-in-crackdown-on-iran-dollar-trade-33ef9f35<author><![CDATA[David S. Cloud]]></author><category>伊朗</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>专有的</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>金融服务</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>伊朗</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>银行业</category><category>信用</category><category>金融服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Tries to Reassure U.S. Amid Speculation Around Missing Foreign Minister]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>前驻华盛顿大使秦刚已三周多没有公开露面<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066232"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819750?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">直到最近，中国外交部长秦刚还是北京驻华盛顿的最高特使。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托马斯·彼得/新闻池</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066232"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lingling-wei" itemprop="url" rel="author">魏玲玲</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 19 日下午 5:18（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>围绕中国领导人习近平精心挑选的外交部长的下落，北京方面向华盛顿保证，尽管这位外交官不再出现在公众视野中，但近期高层接触的缓和仍将继续下去。</p><p>直到最近，中国外交部长秦刚还是北京驻华盛顿的最高特使，已经超过三周没有公开露面，他缺席了重大外交活动，引发了中国国内外对他遭遇的猜测。这种不确定性是在中国和美国一直试图重启两个世界大国之间的高层交往的脆弱时刻出现的。</p><p>上周在印度尼西亚举行的国际外长会议上，秦的缺席尤其引人注目，他原定在那里会见美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯。秦的职位由中共政治局精英成员、中国最高外交官员王毅接替。</p><p>知情人士称，王告诉布林肯，57 岁的秦因“健康原因”缺席，并重复了中国外交部的公开解释。王毅对美国外长表示，北京将与华盛顿保持开放的沟通渠道。</p><p>布林肯邀请秦在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-months-of-cold-shoulder-china-welcomes-blinken-to-beijing-84b51627?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">上个月美国高级外交官访问北京</a>期间访问美国——秦接受了这一邀请，这是双方继续努力恢复今年早些时候被<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-spy-balloon-over-the-u-s-what-to-know-11675385792?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">疑似中国气球</a>中断的通讯线路的一部分。</p><p>此次会议的日期尚未公布，不过中国官员预计此次会议将在习近平可能前往旧金山参加 11 月份亚太领导人年度峰会之前进行。</p><p>当被问及秦的缺席时，国务院发言人马修·米勒周一表示，布林肯在与王会面时“表达了最良好的祝愿”，希望尽快见到他。</p><p>中国外交部针对置评请求发出了一份简短的声明。 “中国的外交活动正在稳步推进，”它说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9F7AF9B6-88BC-4AB6-B4C8-E0CF0C68E116&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">中国外交部长秦刚的长期失踪引发了对其下落的强烈猜测。秦的缺席凸显了世界第二大经济体治理缺乏透明度。照片：Noel Celis/法新社/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>中国最近任命的驻华盛顿大使周三在科罗拉多州阿斯彭的一个论坛上回避了有关秦的问题。</p>正在北京访问的秦大使将会见，谢锋大使说，“让我们拭目以待。”当再次被追问有关秦的问题时，谢表示外交部已经向媒体通报了情况。 “谢谢你的照顾，”他说。<p></p><p>外交部长最后一次露面是在6月25日，当时秦国在俄罗斯发生拙劣的武装叛乱后不久会见了越南和斯里兰卡外长以及俄罗斯副外长鲁登科·安德烈·尤列维奇。秦原定于7月10日在北京会见欧盟外交政策负责人何塞普·博雷尔，但北京五天前取消了此次访问，且没有任何解释。</p><p> 7月初，财政部长珍妮特·耶伦访问北京期间，秦没有会见她。他还缺席了与美国气候特使约翰·克里的会晤，克里原定于周三结束对中国为期四天的访问。</p><p>秦从公共舞台上的消失引发了人们对世界第二大经济体治理的新质疑，而此时共产党<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-locks-information-on-the-country-inside-a-black-box-9c039928?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">却加倍保守</a>秘密，使得获取有关中国境内正在发生的事情的信息变得越来越困难。</p><p>秦被认为是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-promotes-u-s-ambassador-to-foreign-minister-11672409545?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">习近平值得信赖的助手</a>，他在不到两年的时间里从中国驻美国大使晋升为北京外交部长——在一个传统上除了政治关系之外还重视经验的体制中，这样的晋升速度异常快。</p><p>去年年底，习近平提拔秦出任外交部长，当时这位最高领导人开始了他打破<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-xi-claims-third-term-as-communist-party-leader-11666499842?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">常规的第三个任期</a>。一位知情人士表示，这位中国领导人特别看重秦在担任驻华盛顿高级特使期间“很好地表达中国立场”的能力。</p><p>秦与最高领导人的密切关系使得他的缺席变得更加耐人寻味。信息空白引发了社交媒体上的激烈猜测，其中包括围绕婚外情可能性的猜测。</p><p>外交部于7月11日首次提及秦失踪事件，当时外交部在例行新闻发布会上透露，秦因“健康原因”不会参加上周在雅加达举行的国际外长会议，但没有透露任何细节。从那时起，外交部发言人就回避了有关秦的问题，最近在每日新闻发布会的记录中省略了对这位外交部长的提及。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="488" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819748?width=700&amp;height=488" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 6月18日，美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯在北京会见中国外交部长秦刚。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Leah Millis/新闻中心</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在不透明的中国体制中，与健康相关的问题通常被作为高级官员缺席的理由。党内人士表示，这种解释通常是真实的，尽管有时可以掩盖政治问题。 2012年2月，内陆大城市重庆市公安局前局长王立军失踪，市政府称他正在接受“ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/BL-CJB-15144?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">休假式治疗</a>”，以缓解压力和过度劳累。事实上，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303459004577362360212353368?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">已逃往附近城市成都的美国领事馆</a>寻求庇护。</p><p>奥巴马政府国家安全委员会前中国和亚洲问题顾问瑞安·哈斯(Ryan Hass)表示，秦的失踪让人想起“与中国官僚政治相关的鸭子游泳的形象——水面上平静，水面下猛烈踢动。”</p><p>尽管如此，现任华盛顿布鲁金斯学会中国中心主任的哈斯表示，秦的缺席“不会显着改变美中外交交往的基调或实质”。他表示，中国外交部长的职责是在海外阐明和执行中国的政策，但他并不是这些政策的唯一制定者。</p><p>连日来，外交部长王毅多次代行外交部长职务。周一，当中国领导人在北京会见菲律宾前总统罗德里戈·杜特尔特时，王毅和外交部副部长与习近平会面。一天后，王会见了克里。</p><p>北京今年的外交优先事项是为习近平出席旧金山亚太经合组织峰会铺平道路，并可能在那里与拜登总统进行一对一会面。这一优先事项，加上中国经济的疲软，使中国领导层有动力重新与美国接触</p><p><em>—Charles Hutzler 和 Wenxin Fan 对本文做出了贡献。</em></p><p>写信给 Lingling Wei，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Lingling.Wei@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Lingling.Wei@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 21:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-us-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-us-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971<author><![CDATA[Lingling Wei]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>秦刚</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Blasts Hit Military Base in Russian-Occupied Crimea]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>乌克兰袭击连接半岛与俄罗斯的桥梁后发生爆炸，导致疏散<figure><img src="https://www.wsj.com/articles/[object" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>俄罗斯连续第二晚对敖德萨发动猛烈的无人机和导弹袭击。乌克兰官员表示，袭击袭击了一个粮油码头，并引发了该市郊区的一个仓库起火。照片：Oleksandr Gimanov/法新社/盖蒂图片社<span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066046"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066046"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/isabel-coles" itemprop="url" rel="author">伊莎贝尔·科尔斯</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-malsin" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·马尔辛</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anastasiia-malenko" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿纳斯塔西娅·马伦科</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 19 日下午 2:31（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/blasts-hit-military-base-in-russian-occupied-crimea-c9c1ffc1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>周三，在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bridge-between-russia-and-crimea-damaged-in-overnight-strike-a3431b88?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰袭击连接克里米亚和俄罗斯的一座桥梁几天后，俄罗斯</a>占领的克里米亚的一个军事基地发生爆炸，基辅军队正在战场上奋力夺取阵地，爆炸远远地蔓延到前线后方。</p><p>几小时前，在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-says-it-is-pulling-out-of-ukraine-grain-deal-68190d1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">莫斯科退出确保乌克兰粮食出口通过黑海安全通道的国际协议</a>后，俄罗斯连续第二晚对乌克兰港口城市敖德萨进行了一系列导弹和无人机袭击。</p><p>俄罗斯政府周三再次对前往乌克兰的货船发出威胁，称将考虑所有此类船只可能携带军事物资。俄罗斯国防部还在一份书面声明中表示，黑海部分地区，包括国际水域地区，已被宣布为“航行危险”。</p><p>周三小麦期货上涨 8%。</p><p>俄罗斯国家通讯社塔斯社称，克里米亚的爆炸发生在半岛东部基洛夫斯基地区。俄罗斯任命的克里米亚州长谢尔盖·阿克肖诺夫 (Sergey Aksyonov) 表示，由于军事训练场发生火灾，2000 多名居民正在疏散，但没有透露原因。克里米亚鞑靼人社区负责人雷法特·丘巴罗夫表示，这是一个弹药储存设施。</p><p>基辅没有发表评论。本周早些时候，乌克兰声称对刻赤大桥的一次海军无人机袭击负责，这次袭击展示了其对前线后方进行远距离打击的能力。这次袭击是自去年二月俄罗斯入侵以来该桥第二次瘫痪，此次袭击发生在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰反攻</a>之中，反攻进展速度比基辅及其盟国所希望的要慢。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819765?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">爆炸发生地附近克里米亚的交警。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Andrei Rubtsov/TASS/ZUMA Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>乌克兰空军表示，俄罗斯连夜向乌克兰发射了由 30 枚巡航导弹、32 架伊朗制造的神风特攻队无人机和一枚机载导弹组成的连夜攻击。乌克兰空军称，共有 37 架无人机和导弹被乌克兰防空系统击落，其中几架袭击了敖德萨港。</p><p>敖德萨地区军事当局表示，该港口的一个粮油码头遭到袭击，装载设备受损。那里的紧急服务部门正在努力扑灭大火。</p><p>乌克兰最大的粮食出口商Kernel表示，其位于切尔诺莫斯克港的粮食储存和转运设施遭受严重损坏，可能需要12个月才能修复。据称，港口火灾部分烧毁了该公司约 6 万吨粮食。</p><p>乌克兰农业部长米科拉·索尔斯基和其他乌克兰官员公布的照片显示，港口的粮仓和其他建筑遭到火灾损坏。国际公司的资产也在袭击中受到打击，其中包括加拿大谷物公司 Viterra 拥有的一个谷物码头。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1216" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/a9ba2a0b-9980-4b33-a5e9-29503591b18a-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>乌克兰国防部副部长汉娜·马利亚尔将最近对敖德萨的袭击与俄罗斯退出粮食协议联系起来。</p><p> “俄罗斯人的策略之一是发射无人机和导弹来耗尽我们的防空系统，”马利亚尔在接受采访时说。 “我们全国范围内都存在防空短缺。有些类型的导弹我们无法击落，”她补充道，她指的是该国没有被能够击落弹道火箭的爱国者防空系统覆盖的部分地区。</p><p>乌克兰总统</p>弗拉基米尔·泽连斯基周三表示，他已责成军方加强港口安全，并要求合作伙伴加大对俄罗斯的压力，要求其恢复粮食出口。<p></p><p>美国周三宣布了一项价值 13 亿美元的新基辅安全计划，其中包括帮助乌克兰保护其港口的设备。</p><p>黑海粮食协定是近 17 个月战争中为数不多的外交成功之一。在联合国和土耳其的斡旋下，该协议允许乌克兰于去年八月恢复从三个黑海港口运输食品，而几个月前，俄罗斯的入侵导致这些出口停止。</p><p>联合国表示，由于乌克兰是世界上最大的小麦、玉米和葵花籽油出口国之一，该协议帮助全球粮食价格下降了 23% 以上，并缓解了人们对战争将加剧全球饥饿危机的担忧。</p><p>该协议还禁止袭击参与该协议的乌克兰三个港口和船只。莫斯科退出该协议引发了人们对俄罗斯加剧对乌克兰港口和粮食出口基础设施的袭击的担忧。</p><p>乌克兰官员表示，新一轮袭击表明俄罗斯试图在冲突中使用粮食作为武器。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819768?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰敖德萨附近，当地居民正在清理受损公寓楼的废墟。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：STRINGER/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>乌克兰高级官员米哈伊洛·波多利亚克指责俄罗斯试图破坏世界粮食安全，并表示莫斯科“蓄意、故意袭击粮食码头和其他港口设施”。主要目标是摧毁乌克兰粮食运输的可能性。”</p><p>美国国务院表示，俄罗斯退出该协议是为了在经济上惩罚乌克兰，迫使其他国家在战争期间与莫斯科站在一起，并增加俄罗斯从其食品出口中获得的利润，该利润创历史新高。</p><p> “很明显，俄罗斯继续使用粮食作为战争武器。这一次，影响不仅是乌克兰人民，还包括全球粮食供应和价格，”美国国务院发言人马修·米勒周二在华盛顿表示。</p><p>欧盟委员会主席乌苏拉·冯德莱恩对俄罗斯终止该协议的举动表示深切关注。 “风险在于，这会给全球许多脆弱国家带来粮食不安全，”她说。</p><p>该协议的未来仍然充满不确定性。帮助达成初步协议的土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安本周早些时候表示，他将努力说服俄罗斯总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>重新加入该协议。</p><p>这一安排的破裂对埃尔多安来说是一个挑战，他指出该协议是他的关键外交成就之一，此前一年他一直试图弥合俄罗斯与西方之间的分歧，与俄罗斯和乌克兰建立密切关系。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="459" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819764?width=700&amp;height=459" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">克里米亚基洛夫斯基军事训练场发生爆炸，冒出浓烟和火焰。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：STRINGER/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>最近几周，埃尔多安再次表现出挑战普京的意愿，本月早些时候欢迎乌克兰总统来到伊斯坦布尔，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sweden-races-to-secure-turkish-support-for-nato-bid-2452c14f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">批准瑞典</a>加入北大西洋公约组织。这些举措是在瓦格纳准军事组织在俄罗斯发动武装叛乱之后采取的，这使得普京显得更加孤立。</p><p>俄罗斯外交部给了联合国一个90天的期限来满足其要求，其中包括将俄罗斯农业银行重新连接到Swift国际支付系统，以及重启一条通过敖德萨港从俄罗斯经乌克兰出口氨的管道。</p><p>西方和乌克兰官员一直对俄罗斯的要求持怀疑态度，他们指出，在莫斯科暂停交易之前，克里姆林宫拒绝了欧盟和联合国提出的将农业银行的一家子公司与环球银行金融电信协会重新连接的提议。乌克兰不愿恢复通过氨管道的出口，因为这将涉及将大量高爆炸物运送到敖德萨港，造成安全隐患。</p><p>乌克兰呼吁在没有俄罗斯的情况下，在土耳其和联合国的合作下继续签署该协议，但在克里姆林宫本周表示无法再保证该协议之后，目前尚不清楚这三个国家将如何确保穿越黑海的船只的安全。区域内船舶的安全。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="882" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819767?width=1260&amp;height=882" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">消防员在敖德萨遭到袭击的储存设施现场工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乌克兰总统新闻社/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine">—Matthew Luxmoore 和 Alistair MacDonald 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Isabel Coles ( <a href="mailto:isabel.coles@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">isabel.coles@wsj.com</a> )、Jared Malsin ( <a href="mailto:jared.malsin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jared.malsin@wsj.com</a> ) 和 Anastasiia Malenko ( <a href="mailto:anastasiia.malenko@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anastasiia.malenko@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 18:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/blasts-hit-military-base-in-Russian-占领-crimea-c9c1ffc1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/blasts-hit-military-base-in-Russian-占领-crimea-c9c1ffc1<author><![CDATA[Isabel ColesJared MalsinAnastasiia Malenko]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>容量</category><category>设施</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ex-Venezuelan Spy Chief Extradited to U.S. on Drug Charges After Long Manhunt]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>雨果“鸡”卡瓦哈尔可以向美国检察官提供委内瑞拉高级官员的犯罪证据<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067440"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819862?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">雨果·卡瓦哈尔（Hugo Carvajal），摄于 2019 年，周三从西班牙被引渡到美国。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：泳池/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067440"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kejal-vyas" itemprop="url" rel="author">Kejal Vyas</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/juan-forero" itemprop="url" rel="author">Juan Forero</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 19 日下午 2:13 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-venezuelan-spy-chief-extradited-to-u-s-on-drug-charges-after-long-manhunt-9f17954d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>哥伦比亚波哥大——据美国司法部称，委内瑞拉前间谍头目乌戈·卡瓦哈尔因<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venezuelan-officials-suspected-of-turning-country-into-global-cocaine-hub-1431977784?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">涉嫌与毒品恐怖分子勾结贩运可卡因而</a>长期受到美国通缉，周三从西班牙被引渡到美国。</p><p>知情人士称，卡瓦哈尔是总统乌戈·查韦斯 (Hugo Chávez) 的亲信，直至 2013 年去世。卡瓦哈尔可以向美国检察官提供委内瑞拉独裁政权中参与可卡因走私、腐败和洗钱活动的人物信息。</p><p> 63岁的卡瓦哈尔因脖子太长而被称为“El Pollo”或“鸡”，他多次否认美国的指控，称这些指控是出于政治动机。卡瓦哈尔的辩护律师扎卡里·马古利斯-奥努马表示，卡瓦哈尔预计将于周四在纽约南区地方法院出庭，并表示不认罪。</p><p> “为他人作证——这才是真正的价值所在，”一位与卡瓦哈尔关系密切并曾与美国缉毒人员合作过的人士表示。 “他了解这个机构中的人，”他说，并解释说卡瓦哈尔会了解委内瑞拉政府高层的毒品贩运和盗贼统治。</p><p>自2019年以来，卡瓦哈尔在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venezuelan-official-breaks-with-maduro-11550791292?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与查韦斯的继任者尼古拉斯·马杜罗总统决裂</a>并逃离委内瑞拉后，一直在马德里<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-venezuela-military-spy-chief-arrested-11555100543?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">反对引渡程序</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819863?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">西班牙警方在马德里的这座大楼里逮捕了雨果·卡瓦哈尔。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马努·费尔南德斯/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>知情人士称，卡瓦哈尔长期担任这个南美国家军事反情报部门的负责人，使美国调查人员能够深入了解委内瑞拉政权的内部运作及其与哥伦比亚毒品走私者、马克思主义游击队、军火商和国际洗钱活动的关系。曾处理美国针对委内瑞拉官员的案件。</p><p>曾调查卡瓦哈尔的前美国缉毒局驻委内瑞拉专员韦斯利·塔博尔 (Wesley Tabor) 表示：“当你看看他能提供司法范围之外的情报时，你会发现其中的内容非常丰富。”</p><p> “这些信息可能会导致世界各地各种犯罪组织的瓦解和瓦解，”现任佛罗里达州名人咨询集团负责人的塔博尔说。</p><p>卡瓦哈尔被引渡之际，美国一直向马杜罗施压，要求其恢复与反对派的谈判，以便明年举行自由公正的总统选举。但马杜罗对华盛顿的制裁和对政权高级官员的起诉感到愤怒，反而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venezuela-bans-a-top-opposition-figure-from-public-office-11373568?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">取消了主要反对派候选人的</a>竞选资格，并禁止欧洲选举观察员参加。</p><p> 2020年，美国纽约南区检察官<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-indicts-venezuelan-president-nicolas-maduro-on-allegations-of-drug-trafficking-11585236443?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">指控马杜罗</a>、卡瓦哈尔和另一名委内瑞拉高级官员迪奥斯达多·卡贝洛(Diosdado Cabello)，</p>被指控与哥伦比亚贩毒集团合作，向美国“大量”输送可卡因，并利用该药物“作为针对美国的武器”。<p></p><p>马杜罗政府否认了这些指控，称其为“一系列肮脏、虚假的指控”。</p><p>委内瑞拉愤怒谴责<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/deal-maker-for-venezuelas-maduro-regime-extradited-to-u-s-11634432668?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2021 年引渡</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/key-financier-of-venezuelas-maduro-regime-arrested-11592078537?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">马杜罗的重要金融家</a>亚历克斯·萨博 (Alex Saab)，美国指控他洗钱并帮助委内瑞拉政府逃避美国的经济制裁。</p><p>萨博也否认了这些指控。但委内瑞拉前检察官和熟悉其案件的人士表示，他和卡瓦哈尔一样，掌握着机密信息，可以帮助美国情报和缉毒人员调查马杜罗政权与伊朗和俄罗斯等其他美国对手的不正当金融交易，这些交易帮助加拉加斯比美国更长久。制裁。</p><p>美国调查人员表示，他们一直在煞费苦心地拼凑有关该政权涉嫌与贩毒有联系的信息。</p><p>上个月，卡瓦哈尔的同案被告之一、委内瑞拉退役将军克利弗·阿尔卡拉 (Cliver Alcalá) 告诉纽约一家法院，他向现已解散的反叛组织哥伦比亚革命武装部队提供保护和武器，包括榴弹发射器。或哥伦比亚革命武装力量。阿尔卡拉承认了美国与哥伦比亚革命武装力量勾结的指控，并成为马杜罗的批评者，并向美国执法部门自首。</p><p>事实证明，卡瓦哈尔更加难以捉摸，带领美国官员进行了长期的国际搜捕。 2011年，纽约美国检察官指控他密谋于2006年通过墨西哥向美国走私5.6吨可卡因。</p><p> 2014年，卡瓦哈尔因美国逮捕令被拘留在荷兰加勒比海阿鲁巴岛，当时马杜罗政府正准备任命他为委内瑞拉特使。委内瑞拉政府向阿鲁巴施压，要求释放他，他返回委内瑞拉后受到了马杜罗精心策划的英雄般的欢迎。</p><p>卡瓦哈尔在公开谴责马杜罗在政治抗议期间涉嫌侵犯人权后，于 2019 年与政府分裂。</p><p>卡瓦哈尔逃往西班牙后，于 2019 年 4 月再次因美国指控被捕。几个月后， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spain-releases-former-venezuelan-spy-chief-wanted-by-u-s-on-drug-charges-11568653834?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">他在引渡程序正在进行中被西班牙法院释放</a>，并躲藏起来。</p><p>写信给 Kejal Vyas <a href="mailto:kejal.vyas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（kejal.vyas@wsj.com）</a>和 Juan Forero（ <a href="mailto:juan.forero@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">juan.forero@wsj.com）</a></p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>委内瑞拉前间谍头子乌戈·卡瓦哈尔现年 63 岁。本文的早期版本错误地称他是 61 岁。（于 7 月 19 日更正）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 18:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-venezuelan-spy-chief-extradited-to-us-on-drug-charges-after-long-manhunt-9f17954d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-venezuelan-spy-chief-extradited-to-us-on-drug-charges-after-long-manhunt-9f17954d<author><![CDATA[Kejal VyasJuan Forero]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>腐败</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>毒品贩运/交易</category><category>洗钱</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>Espionage</category><category> Trafficking/Smuggling</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Hugo Carvajal</category><category> Hugo Chávez</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>corruption</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>drug trafficking</category><category> dealing</category><category> money laundering</category><category> financial crime</category><category> espionage</category><category> trafficking</category><category> smuggling</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kerry’s China Trip Restores Talks on Climate Change But Falls Short on Agreement]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Visit by the US climate envoy tests Beijing&#39;s willingness to find common ground <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067204"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=AEFDD20E-B8EC-4F14-B1AA-8439E0D73B67&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fkerrys-china-trip-restores-talks-on-climate-change-but-falls-short-on-agreement-f89be8e2&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">总统气候特使约翰·克里在此次访问中会见了中国国务院总理李强，旨在试图重振陷入僵局的气候变化合作。照片：Florence Lo/路透社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067204"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sha-hua" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sha Hua</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 1:43 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kerrys-china-trip-restores-talks-on-climate-change-but-falls-short-on-agreement-f89be8e2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> John Kerry, the US special envoy on climate, concluded talks in China that pushed forward the two powers&#39; tentative effort to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-china-start-talking-again-with-global-economic-order-at-stake-9b49a10b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reset fraught ties</a> and tested Beijing&#39;s willingness to find common ground on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-sets-heat-record-as-john-kerry-arrives-to-discuss-climate-6a35c686?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fighting climate change</a> .</p><p> Kerry saw a parade of high-level Chinese officials and spent long hours in closed-door meetings with his counterpart during his three days in Beijing. Both sides came away citing a readiness for future discussions on climate change after nearly a year of little contact due to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/restricting-chip-sales-to-china-could-backfire-on-u-s-industry-group-says-dbb7b8df?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beijing&#39;s anger</a> with Washington <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwans-vice-president-plans-stop-in-the-u-s-at-a-delicate-moment-886e484b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">over Taiwan</a> , technology and other issues.</p><p> “We came here to unstick what had been stuck,” Kerry told reporters Wednesday. “And indeed, we did succeed.”</p><p> While both sides agreed to future collaboration, Kerry said, they couldn&#39;t finalize all the details. Nor did he get an audience with Chinese leader Xi Jinping, who instead attended a conference on environmental protection and sent a signal on Beijing&#39;s limits for engagement.</p><p> In remarks to that gathering, Xi reiterated <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-ambitious-climate-goals-collide-with-reality-imperiling-global-efforts-11635346919?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China&#39;s goals</a> to see its climate-warming emissions peak before 2030 and become carbon neutral before 2060. But he underscored that his government would proceed on its own timetable despite pressure from the Biden administration to accelerate the time frame.</p><p> “The pathway, pace and the vigor with which to achieve these goals should and must be determined by ourselves, and free from outside interference,” Xi said, according to state media reports. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819853?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> China&#39;s top foreign-policy official, Wang Yi, said that the climate issue couldn&#39;t be detached from the overall state of bilateral relations with the US</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: FLORENCE LO/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Biden administration has marked out climate, along with the global economy and public health, as areas ripe for cooperation with Beijing to offset the US and China&#39;s bare-knuckled rivalry <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-looks-to-restrict-chinas-access-to-cloud-computing-to-protect-advanced-technology-f771613?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">over technology</a> and global primacy.</p><p> In getting Beijing&#39;s assent to talk more, Kerry met <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-months-of-cold-shoulder-china-welcomes-blinken-to-beijing-84b51627?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the low bar</a> set by Secretary of State <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-jinping-to-meet-blinken-monday-as-u-s-china-resume-high-level-engagement-c898f541?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Antony Blinken</a> and Treasury Secretary <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellen-trip-aids-fragile-effort-by-u-s-china-to-keep-talking-9b78ea55?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Janet Yellen</a> on their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellen-trip-aids-fragile-effort-by-u-s-china-to-keep-talking-9b78ea55?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">recent trips to Beijing</a> as the two governments resume high-level contacts.</p><p> Kerry said he and his Chinese interlocutors were already discussing the next two sets of meetings ahead of the upcoming climate summit in Dubai at the end of the year. Points of further discussion, he said, include new emission goals for 2035 and ways to reduce emissions of methane and other non-carbon dioxide emissions. China&#39;s use of coal, Kerry said, remains a contentious issue.</p><p> For this visit, the concrete results are less important than the fact there was sustained, constructive communication, said Michael Davidson, assistant professor at the School of Global Policy and Strategy at the University of California, San Diego.</p><p> “It&#39;s a stepping stone to more robust engagement on climate,” Davidson said. Further commitments, he said, could be announced in Dubai or at a potential meeting between Xi and President Biden late this year.</p><p> As the world&#39;s two largest greenhouse-gas emitters, Kerry said, the US and China recognize the urgency of tackling climate change as swaths of the US, Europe and China <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">experience record heat waves</a> in recent days.</p><p> In their meeting Tuesday, Chinese Premier</p> Li Qiang, the country&#39;s No. 2-ranked leader, said that the two countries should “act promptly to form a joint force to deal with climate change.”<p></p><p> Republicans and other critics of the Biden administration have been critical of the recent high-level outreach as engaging in empty talk without advancing US interests.</p><p> When Kerry appeared before the House Foreign Affairs Committee last week, its chairman, Rep. Michael McCaul (R., Texas), pointed to China&#39;s human-rights abuses and its unwillingness to make bigger cuts in carbon-dioxide emissions.</p><p> McCaul also faulted China for keeping its developing country status, as designated by the United Nations, and for insisting that it not be held to the same standards as developed countries, despite being the world&#39;s second largest economy and largest greenhouse gas emitter.</p><p> Since taking up the envoy post, Kerry has tried to keep climate issues separate from wider diplomatic disputes between the two countries. He told Chinese officials that he would convey Beijing&#39;s concerns to Washington but wanted to steer clear of contentious issues, including concerns over forced labor in the clean-energy supply chain or rising tensions in the Taiwan Strait.</p><p> He told reporters that he hopes “nothing will get in the way of us dealing with the climate crisis.”</p><p> In contrast, Chinese officials have seen Kerry as a way to reach Biden and leverage administration <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-administration-targets-power-plant-emissions-in-new-climate-initiative-cb635552?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">interest in climate change</a> to influence US policy.</p><p> China&#39;s top foreign-policy official, Wang Yi, told Kerry during their meeting Tuesday that the climate issue couldn&#39;t be detached from the overall state of bilateral relations.</p><p> Wang also called Kerry “an old friend”—a reference to their overlapping past tenures as their countries&#39; foreign ministers.</p><p> Kerry&#39;s overall smooth interactions with Chinese interlocutors during his trip will only confirm his critics&#39; views that he is soft on China, said Ilaria Mazzocco, a senior fellow at the Center for Strategic and International Studies, a Washington, DC, think tank.</p><p> Competition over clean-energy technology, such as solar panels and batteries, as well as the critical minerals necessary to produce them, might further narrow the space for cooperation, said Mazzocco.</p><p> “This may make it even harder to delink climate from other issues in the relationship,” she said.</p><p> Cooperating on climate change had been a rare bright spot in the testy relationship between the countries. Kerry&#39;s counterpart Xie Zhenhua told Chinese reporters Monday that he and Kerry had spoken to one another 53 times since their respective appointments in early 2021.</p><p> Those frequent interactions ground to a halt after then-House Speaker <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/nancy-pelosi">Nancy Pelosi</a> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/nancy-pelosi-taiwan-visit-china-us-tensions" target="_blank" class="icon none">visited Taiwan</a> last year over Beijing&#39;s vehement objections. The talks resumed again three months later on the sidelines of a global climate gathering in Egypt but were derailed again earlier this year, when Xie suffered a stroke and a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-balloon-used-american-tech-to-spy-on-americans-2e3f5039?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">suspected Chinese spy balloon</a> drifted across the US</p><p> Write to Sha Hua at <a href="mailto:sha.hua@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sha.hua@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 17:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kerrys-china-trip-restores-talks-on-climate-change-but-falls-short-on-agreement-f89be8e2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kerrys-china-trip-restores-talks-on-climate-change-but-falls-short-on-agreement-f89be8e2<author><![CDATA[Sha Hua]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球/世界问题</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> John Kerry</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球的</category><category>世界问题</category><category>政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Travis King, U.S. Soldier Held in North Korea, Had Been Detained in South Korea]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The American&#39;s &#39;willful&#39; entry to the North instead of facing disciplinary actions creates fresh challenge for Washington and Pyongyang <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066508"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D69C17D9-A239-4491-A945-60AAB8A04205&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftravis-king-u-s-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">白宫新闻秘书表示，周二，一名美国陆军一等兵特拉维斯·金 (Travis King) 士兵在参观联合安全区时越过军事分界线，随后美国正在​​与朝鲜当局合作。照片：安东尼·华莱士/法新社/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066508"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dasl-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dasl Yoon</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/timothy-w-martin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Timothy W. Martin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 11:19 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/travis-king-u-s-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> SEOUL—The US soldier <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-us-national-custody-b53b4449?mod=hp_featst_pos4&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">being held in North Korea</a> had faced assault allegations in South Korea last year and spent nearly seven weeks in a detention facility, according to US officials, <strong>&nbsp;</strong> as new details emerged about the legal issues faced by an American who crossed the Korean border.</p><p> The fate of the soldier, identified as Army Private 2nd Class Travis King, has handed Washington a fresh challenge in its relations with Pyongyang as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">tensions have been rising</a> on the Korean Peninsula.</p><p> King, 23, remained in North Korean custody on Wednesday after crossing the border without authorization the previous day while on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-officer-on-a-pink-phone-dials-down-north-korea-tensions-11558287392?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a tour of the Joint Security Area</a> , which is within the Demilitarized Zone separating the two Koreas. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1068" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/867c108b-9cd5-4f9d-b318-b15cf01feec4-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Adm. John Aquilino, the head of US Indo-Pacific Command, said on Tuesday that the military was investigating the situation and that, as far as he knew, the US hadn&#39;t been in contact with North Korea regarding the soldier. North Korea hasn&#39;t commented on King.</p><p>根据金的服役记录，他是一名骑兵侦察兵，自 2021 年 1 月起一直在陆军服役，但没有服役。 He was held at a detention facility in South Korea for 47 days, and spent about a week <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-end-of-small-town-america-in-the-heart-of-seoul-11567503006?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">at Camp Humphreys</a> —a large US Army base in South Korea—before being escorted by military officers to Incheon International Airport, US officials said. On Monday, he had been set to board a flight to Texas, where he would face disciplinary actions and a potential discharge, the officials said.</p><p> King was involved in two alleged assaults, according to a representative at a Seoul court that sentenced him. In September, he allegedly assaulted a South Korean citizen, outside of a nightclub in Hongdae, a popular shopping and nightlife district in Seoul, according to the representative. That incident made headlines in the local media in South Korea, where incidents involving US soldiers often draw attention. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820275?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A photo of Travis King displayed at the home of his grandfather in Kenosha, Wis.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In October, he was involved in another alleged assault, the representative said. As a part of that incident, he allegedly damaged a police car by kicking it while he was in the back seat, the representative said. In February, he was fined $4,000 for that incident.</p><p> King&#39;s mother told ABC News that she was shocked to hear her son had crossed the border into North Korea. “I can&#39;t see Travis doing anything like that,” said Claudine Gates, who lives in Racine, Wis. Gates couldn&#39;t be reached by The Wall Street Journal, and the court representative declined to comment on legal representation.</p><p> A spokesman for the US Forces Korea declined to comment on whether King had been held in a detention facility on the US base, but former USFK officials said it was likely he was held at Camp Humphreys. USFK oversees the 28,500 American military personnel stationed in South Korea.</p><h3> An &#39;inconvenience&#39; for US</h3><p> Key questions remain unanswered as to how King went from being escorted out of South Korea to entering North Korea, in just a single day. It couldn&#39;t be determined how he got out of the airport terminal and, by Tuesday afternoon, ended up on a tour of the JSA, a site of high-profile summits and a major tourist draw. King then ran into North Korea “willfully and without permission,” a USFK spokesman said on Tuesday.</p><p> Washington may be unable to win King&#39;s release, former US officials and close Pyongyang watchers say. Unlike most North Korean prisoner incidents of the past, King voluntarily entered the country, rather than having been arrested for sneaking across the border or defacing state propaganda.</p><p> As a cavalry scout, King would likely have been familiar with a lot of sensitive military operational information, such as details about the US Command and Control or the priorities of his unit, said Evans Revere, a former senior State Department official. King may have also even been briefed on matters such as how Washington and Seoul assess the military capabilities of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">Kim Jong Un</a> &#39;s regime, he added. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820431?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Travis King, in a black shirt and cap, according to Reuters, was among a group of tourists who visited the Demilitarized Zone on Tuesday in Paju, South Korea, before he crossed the border.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: SARAH LESLIE/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “This guy, even though he is fairly low ranking, still has some experience that the North Koreans will be eager to know about,” said Revere, who spent extensive time in South Korea including with the US Air Force.</p><p> The potential information King could share—should he choose to do so—is unlikely to be sensitive intelligence related to war plans or combat-deployment details, Revere added. “But it&#39;s an irritant, an inconvenience and an embarrassment,” he said.</p><p> How North Korea portrays King&#39;s detainment could shed light on what Pyongyang might have planned next, said Rachel Minyoung Lee, a senior analyst for Open Nuclear Network, a research group based in Vienna.</p><p> For prior cases, North Korean state media has taken anywhere from a single day to more than a month to mention American detainees. In many instances, Pyongyang chose to publicize the event in state-media outlets geared for global audiences and held back from reporting the news domestically.</p><p> For King, North Korea could spin his case as an American soldier who grew disenchanted with the US and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-says-he-entered-north-korea-illegally-1418544534?tesla=y&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">wanted to defect for a better life</a> , or state media could stress the “illegal” nature of his crossing the military demarcation line and treat him as a criminal, said Lee, a former senior North Korea analyst for the US government.</p><p> “Much will depend on whether North Korea views it as a good propaganda opportunity,” she said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="407" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819753?width=700&amp;height=407" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A military check point near the Demilitarized Zone separating the two Koreas.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jeon Heon-Kyun/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> Previous Americans held in North Korea</h3><p> At least six US military servicemen have opted to defect to North Korea over the decades, with all but one of them having crossed through the DMZ. Before King, no American soldier had willfully crossed into North Korea in decades.</p><p> In 1965, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-a-u-s-soldier-impromptu-trip-to-north-korea-lasted-four-decades-1513350001?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Army sergeant Charles Jenkins</a> deserted his post in South Korea and fled to the North across the DMZ. He was used for propaganda in North Korea, where he was cast as a capitalist villain in films. After spending nearly four decades in North Korea, he surrendered to US military authorities in Japan and was dishonorably discharged from the US military.</p><p> Other Americans have been held captive in North Korea, facing dire humanitarian conditions. Otto Warmbier, an American university student, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/otto-warmbier-american-detainee-released-by-north-korea-has-died-1497905282?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">was detained and imprisoned</a> in North Korea in 2016 for allegedly defacing a political poster while on a tour. Warmbier died in 2017 upon returning to the US with brain damage.</p><p> The last American to have been detained by North Korea was Bruce Byron Lowrance in 2018. Lowrance was deported by the Kim regime after roughly a month of confinement—an unusually brisk turnaround. The move came months after Kim met former President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> for the first time in Singapore, and ahead of a second nuclear summit with the US in Vietnam where talks abruptly broke down. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="499" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819953?width=700&amp;height=499" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Army sergeant Charles Jenkins arrived in Japan in 2004 after living for nearly four decades in North Korea following his desertion.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Eric Talmadge/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> North Korea does face some risk holding on to King, given his status as an active US soldier. Any personal injury, illness or something worse happening to King under the watch of the Kim regime could trigger a major backlash among the American public, said Ramon Pacheco Pardo, the KF-VUB Korea chair at the Brussels School of Governance.</p><p> “This is not like a missile test, a nuclear test, or an American tourist, American pastor,” Pacheco Pardo said. “You&#39;re talking about someone who serves in the armed forces, and we know how important this is in the US”</p><p> Historically, North Korea has coerced confessions from American captives, forcing them to admit they were spying for the US or confess to crimes they hadn&#39;t committed.</p><p> In prior decades, former Presidents Jimmy Carter and Bill Clinton went to North Korea to negotiate the release of Americans. In return, the Kim regime enjoyed a boost to national prestige while demonstrating its power and ability to compel such high-level visits.</p><p> Seongmin Lee, director of the Korea Desk at the Human Rights Foundation in Seoul, left North Korea a little over a decade ago when he was in his early 20s, and he recalls North Korea&#39;s portrayal <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124938154079404323?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">of Clinton&#39;s 2009 visit</a> to win the release of two Americans. Lee remembers North Korean state media stressing the two Americans had committed a crime while reinforcing that a former US president had come to Pyongyang to meet Kim Jong Il, North Korea&#39;s then-leader, to offer a personal apology and an in-person greeting.</p><p> “The impression people got is that these high-profile politicians come to Pyongyang to meet the leader because our leader is great,” said Lee.</p><p> Write to Dasl Yoon at <a href="mailto:dasl.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dasl.yoon@wsj.com</a> and Timothy W. Martin at <a href="mailto:Timothy.Martin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Timothy.Martin@wsj.com</a></p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>Travis King&#39;s identity in a handout photo was reported by Reuters. An earlier version of this article incorrectly attributed it to the Associated Press. (Corrected on July 19)</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 15:19:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/travis-king-us-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/travis-king-us-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529<author><![CDATA[Dasl YoonTimothy W. Martin]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>特拉维斯·金</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Thai Political Star Is Blocked From Power]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Pita Limjaroenrat sought to become prime minister after his upstart party beat the country&#39;s military-backed establishment in elections <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066222"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819845?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Supporters of the Move Forward political party gathered in Bangkok on Wednesday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sakchai Lalit/Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066222"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/feliz-solomon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Feliz Solomon</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 9:41 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/thai-political-star-is-blocked-from-power-thwarting-democracy-movement-9b724830"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Two months ago when Pita Limjaroenrat&#39;s upstart party handily <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/thailand-pro-democracy-candidates-push-to-break-military-grip-in-election-f44a367f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">defeated its military-backed opponents</a> in national elections, the results were widely seen as a leap forward for democracy in a country whose powerful army and its royalist backers have long resisted change.</p><p> It has become clear in recent days that, despite his electoral success, the 42-year-old youth icon won&#39;t run Thailand&#39;s new government. Last week, an army-appointed senate <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/thailands-breakout-political-star-meets-resistance-as-he-takes-on-military-and-monarchy-7435d9e5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">blocked Pita&#39;s first bid</a> to become prime minister. On Wednesday, his quest to lead the country all but ended as a court suspended him from parliament and lawmakers decided against allowing him the chance to stand in a second parliamentary vote for the top job.</p><p> Pita&#39;s challenges show the persistent obstacles that democracy faces in Southeast Asia, where countries such as Myanmar, Cambodia, Vietnam and Laos <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-grand-vision-for-a-vast-rail-network-transforms-a-neighboring-country-17f067cc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are ruled by authoritarian regimes</a> . The struggle has been particularly volatile in Thailand, where the military has staged more than a dozen coups over the past century and, in recent years, sought to crush <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-generation-presses-thailands-military-and-monarchy-to-step-away-from-politics-11600266595?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a youth-led movement</a> that has more openly questioned its authority than ever before.</p><p> On Wednesday, hundreds of Pita&#39;s supporters protested outside parliament and in central Bangkok, a glimpse of broader turmoil that may lie ahead. His party, Move Forward, is popular among well-educated and social-media-savvy youths that oppose the army&#39;s grip on politics. Many joined or led pro-democracy demonstrations in recent years to oppose military-backed rule after a 2014 coup. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819844?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Move Forward leader Pita Limjaroenrat, wearing a blue tie, spoke with colleagues in Bangkok on Wednesday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Rungroj Yongrit/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The young people who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/young-harvard-educated-politician-shakes-up-thailands-old-guard-235d1f18?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">powered Move Forward</a> have advocated for bold changes to the nation&#39;s politics and society, representing a seismic generational shift. The party campaigned on sweeping promises to dislodge the military from politics and amend the country&#39;s lèse-majesté law, which makes insulting the monarchy a crime punishable by up to 15 years in prison. The unprecedented proposal energized young people but <strong>&nbsp;</strong> confronted Thailand&#39;s most powerful institution.</p><p> Since the May elections, Pita has been engulfed by challenges his supporters say are part of the establishment&#39;s playbook to oust him from politics. Last week, a day before Pita&#39;s first parliamentary vote for prime minister, election authorities referred to court a case that alleges Pita is ineligible for office because he owned shares in a media company.</p><p> On Wednesday, as the legislature reconvened to discuss a potential second vote on Pita&#39;s candidacy, the court said it was suspending him from parliament while it reviews the case.</p><p> “What happened in parliament and in court today could potentially trigger reactions in the form of street protests and new political upheavals, and Thailand has a history of overreaction by the armed forces,” said Sunai Phasuk, senior Thailand researcher for Human Rights Watch. “Putting these two things together doesn&#39;t bode well for stability and the hopes of restoring democracy that arose after the election.”</p><p> Move Forward captured more seats than any other party in the nationwide vote on May 14. After the stunning result, Pita shored up a coalition of eight parties that backed him for the premiership. The coalition commands a majority in the elected lower house of parliament, but the role of prime minister requires a majority in the bicameral legislature, which also includes a 250-seat senate handpicked by the army. That bloc effectively vetoed Pita&#39;s candidacy last week.</p><p> “It&#39;s clear that in the current system, winning the trust of the people is not enough to run the country,” Pita said on social media on Wednesday. “You need to seek approval from the <strong>&nbsp;</strong> senate first.”</p><p> Pheu Thai, a populist pro-democracy party that came in second place in the election, is expected to put forward its candidate when parliament reconvenes next week. Pheu Thai has said it will likely nominate 60-year-old real estate tycoon Srettha Thavisin as its choice for prime minister.</p><p> The legal actions against Pita pose a broader threat to his political career. In addition to the case about media shares, Pita and Move Forward are also the subject of a separate case in which a lawyer has alleged that they sought to overthrow the government by pledging to amend Thailand&#39;s lèse-majesté law. The case threatens to dissolve the party, which would effectively sideline the biggest challenge to the establishment but would enrage the millions of people who voted for change.</p><p> The events are familiar to Thailand&#39;s democracy supporters. Move Forward&#39;s predecessor was a party called Future Forward that made surprising gains in 2019 elections but was dissolved by a court ruling in 2020. The court held that it violated campaign-finance rules in a case human-rights groups say was politically motivated. Its leader,</p> Thanathorn Juangroongruangkit, had earlier been kicked out of parliament for owning shares in a media company, in a case similar to the one that now threatens Pita.<p></p><p> Pita has previously cast the media shares case as a baseless attempt to block him from power. He has said the shares in question were inherited as part of his late father&#39;s estate, and weren&#39;t sold because they were essentially worthless. The firm stopped operating in 2007 and was delisted from Thailand&#39;s stock exchange in 2014, according to company documents. Pita has said he divested the shares, which were reported to regulators, after the election.</p><p> Pita hasn&#39;t said what actions he plans to take next, but has previously pledged to continue his fight for a government that represents the will of voters.</p><p> “I think Thailand has changed,” Pita said before he left parliament on Wednesday. “It has not been the same since May 14.”</p><p> Write to Feliz Solomon at <a href="mailto:feliz.solomon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">feliz.solomon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 13:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/thai-political-star-is-blocked-from-power-thwarting-democracy-movement-9b724830</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/thai-political-star-is-blocked-from-power-thwarting-democracy-movement-9b724830<author><![CDATA[Feliz Solomon]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Pita Limjaroenrat</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Facing Possible Arrest, Putin Won’t Attend Summit in South Africa]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> South African government has been under pressure from the US and other Western nations for its close ties to Russia <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066258"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="552" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819838?width=860&amp;height=552" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> President Vladimir Putin with South Africa&#39;s President Cyril Ramaphosa. The ICC has issued a warrant for the arrest of the Russian leader.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: ramil sitdikov/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066258"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">Gabriele Steinhauser</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 9:09 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/facing-possible-arrest-putin-wont-attend-brics-summit-in-south-africa-34e637e9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">Vladimir Putin</a> won&#39;t attend a summit with leaders from Brazil, India, China and South Africa in Johannesburg next month, South Africa said Wednesday, resolving a dilemma for the host country, which would have been <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-africas-difficult-choice-should-it-host-putin-f1de2323?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">obliged to arrest the Russian leader</a> under an international warrant.</p><p> A spokesman for South African President Cyril Ramaphosa said Russia would be represented by its foreign minister, Sergei Lavrov, at the August meeting of leaders from the Brics nations “by mutual agreement.”</p><p> The Kremlin didn&#39;t immediately comment on the decision. Putin&#39;s spokesman had previously said that Russia would be represented at the summit at the “proper level” without providing more details.</p><p> Putin&#39;s decision not to attend the summit will come as a relief for the South African government, which has been under pressure from the US and other Western nations, as well as its own opposition parties, over its close ties to Russia.</p><p> As a signatory to the Rome Statute, South Africa would have been obliged to arrest Putin and send him to the International Criminal Court in The Hague, the Netherlands, where prosecutors have accused him of war crimes linked to the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-n-court-issues-arrest-warrant-for-russias-putin-and-another-kremlin-official-d3b9cb8e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">forced deportation of children from Russian-occupied territories in Ukraine</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9642AA64-6915-4C7E-973F-5C48F3D0A8BE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffacing-possible-arrest-putin-wont-attend-brics-summit-in-south-africa-34e637e9&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Videos and photos posted by authorities in occupied Ukrainian regions show children waving Russian flags, studying Russian history and dancing to patriotic Russian songs. WSJ&#39;s Ian Lovett explains the Kremlin&#39;s efforts to re-educate Ukrainian children. Photo composite: Kalvin Ng<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>In March, the ICC issued a warrant to arrest Putin and a senior Kremlin official. It marked the first time the leader of a nuclear superpower has been called to account before the court, an independent institution established in 2002 to end impunity for war crimes, crimes against humanity and genocide.</p><p> South African officials have said in recent weeks that they would prefer for Putin not to attend the summit in person while they continued to look for ways around having to execute the warrant. In an affidavit to a South African court published on Tuesday, Ramaphosa argued that arresting Putin would expose his country to serious risks.</p><p> “Russia has made it clear that the arrest of its sitting president would be tantamount to a declaration of war,” wrote Ramaphosa in the affidavit. “It would be inconsistent with our Constitution to risk engaging in war with Russia,” he added.</p><p> On Wednesday, Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov denied that Russia had made such a threat.</p><p> “No, it didn&#39;t sound like that,” he told reporters during a briefing, according to Russia&#39;s state news agency TASS. “Nobody made anyone understand anything. In this world, it&#39;s absolutely clear to everyone what an attempt to encroach on the head of the Russian state means. Therefore, there&#39;s no need to explain anything to anyone here,” he said.</p><p> Russian Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Maria Zakharova has said that ICC decisions have no meaning for Russia and has described the arrest warrants as legally void.</p><p> Although the US, like Russia, isn&#39;t a party to the Rome Statute, President Biden has said the warrant for Putin was justified. US officials have in recent months also been critical of South Africa&#39;s close relationship with Russia, which dates back to the Soviet Union&#39;s support for the ruling African National Congress&#39;s antiapartheid battle.</p><p> In May, the US ambassador in Pretoria said the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-says-south-africa-supplied-weapons-ammunition-to-russia-c2489d54?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">country had supplied weapons to Russia</a> , an accusation that triggered a drop in the local currency and concern that Washington could end preferential access of some South African goods to the US market. South Africa has said it is investigating the US claims.</p><p> Write to Gabriele Steinhauser at <a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 13:09:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/facing-possible-arrest-putin-wont-attend-brics-summit-in-south-africa-34e637e9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/facing-possible-arrest-putin-wont-attend-brics-summit-in-south-africa-34e637e9<author><![CDATA[Gabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>War Crimes</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>弗拉基米尔普京</category><category>Cyril Ramaphosa</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>war crimes </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Vision for a Vast Rail Network Transforms a Neighboring Country]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> People and investments flow into Laos, making it &#39;more like China&#39; <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817243/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="老挝琅勃拉邦当地人停止出售蘑菇，观看火车穿过湄公河上的一座新桥。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Locals stopped selling mushrooms to watch a train cross a new bridge over the Mekong River in Luang Prabang, Laos. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062426"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062426"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/feliz-solomon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Feliz Solomon</a></span> | Photographs by Lauren DeCicca for The Wall Street Journal</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 8:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-grand-vision-for-a-vast-rail-network-transforms-a-neighboring-country-17f067cc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> BOTEN, Laos—A few years ago, this small town on the border with China was a few dusty lanes surrounded by tropical forests. Now, a nearly $6 billion Chinese-built railroad cuts through it—and a city is rising.</p><p> Dozens of half-constructed office towers and warehouses rise into the skyline. A Chinese developer, Yunnan Haicheng Industrial Group, is pitching the six-square-mile special economic zone where they stand as the gateway between China and Southeast Asia, a place where labor is cheap and exporting is easy, thanks to the new train.</p><p> Jackhammers clamor until nightfall, when they give way to the sounds of Chinese pop music blaring from open-air restaurants where transiting businessmen unwind over beer and spicy peanuts.</p><p> “There&#39;s a Chinese saying that when the whistle blows, it&#39;s worth 10,000 taels of gold,” said He Ming Jia, a senior executive at Yunnan Haicheng. “Chinese investment follows the train.”</p><p> Globally, China&#39;s now decade-old Belt and Road Initiative, or BRI, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-belt-road-debt-11663961638?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has been in retreat</a> , with a number of projects stalled or mired in controversy—at times over allegations of incurring <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hidden-debt-plagues-chinas-belt-and-road-infrastructure-plan-studies-find-11632866461?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">unsustainable debts</a> for developing countries. But in this part of Southeast Asia, it is alive and kicking. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1068" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/eb4e2cde-13c0-46ec-8db3-1b38e1005f4b-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Beijing is casting the 262-mile rail line, which launched in late 2021, as a showcase of how its grand vision for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/railroaded-the-chinese-high-speed-train-network-no-one-else-really-wants-1526644804?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">regionwide rail connectivity</a> can be transformative for the local economy. The plan imagines a China-backed network stretching through Southeast Asia&#39;s agricultural and industrial heartlands—drawing its neighbors into a tighter embrace and binding their economies to its own for decades to come.</p><p> “To China, this is a key mega project. Completion of this railway will demonstrate that BRI remains on track,” said Yu Hong, a senior research fellow at the East Asian Institute of the National University of Singapore. “This is very much the message that China wants to convey to the world.”</p><p> The Laos-China Railway is the first leg of Beijing&#39;s plan. It runs between the Chinese commercial hub of Kunming and Vientiane, the Lao capital near the border with Thailand. Beijing aims to extend it further south, linking to the Thai and Malaysian capitals, Bangkok and Kuala Lumpur.</p><p> China also plans to upgrade a railroad that runs east through Cambodia—and build another running west from Kunming to the coast of Myanmar. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818984?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Developers describe the nascent Boten Special Economic Zone in Laos as a new gateway between China and Southeast Asia. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818988?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A worker in Laos inspects a cargo train headed for China.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Momentum in Laos, China hopes, will kick-start progress elsewhere. Construction is under way in Thailand and Malaysia, but has faced local skepticism and delays.</p><p> Thai transportation officials have said a section from Bangkok to the Lao border will be complete by 2028. Negotiations on upgrading an existing rail link between Bangkok and Kuala Lumpur are continuing. A China-built railroad connecting Malaysia&#39;s coasts is expected to be completed by the end of 2026, after years in limbo.</p><p> The World Bank has said the Laos-China Railway could raise the Southeast Asian country&#39;s aggregate income by up to 21% over the long term, if it is managed well. But <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/debt-troubles-in-laos-reveal-economic-turmoil-in-developing-world-11657877403?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">economists are still at odds</a> over its financial rationale.</p><p> Laos was already struggling to pay back lenders when it borrowed $1.54 billion from China&#39;s Export-Import Bank to fund its share. And it is unlikely to make much revenue from the train itself, owning only a 30% stake while three Chinese companies own the rest. According to the World Bank, the country&#39;s total debt has reached “critical levels,” around $14.5 billion in 2021, with China accounting for about half of its external debt. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D53246B2-FCE2-4490-BA93-E459B9066FAE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-grand-vision-for-a-vast-rail-network-transforms-a-neighboring-country-17f067cc&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> China has some of the fastest—and busiest—trains in the world. But despite having some of the same technology, the US has struggled to develop its own high-speed rail. WSJ explores the barriers hindering its development. Photo Illustration: Mike Janson<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“A lot of other investment is needed in order to really make this work,” said Mariza Cooray, a senior economist at the Indo-Pacific Development Centre at the Lowy Institute, an Australia-based think tank. Complementary infrastructure such as roads and more capacity to capture tourism revenue will require even more borrowing, she said, adding: “They&#39;re really in a kind of debt spiral.”</p><p> The country&#39;s “growing and unsustainable debt burden” is limiting its ability to invest in vital health and education services, said Ben Bland, the Asia-Pacific program director for Chatham House, a UK-based think tank.</p><p> “These are real and pressing short-term pressures, while the returns from the rail project will only be clear in the long term,” Bland said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818980?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Passengers travel north on the new Laos-China Railway from Vang Vieng, Laos, toward the Chinese border. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817244?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Lao day laborers who work for a Chinese silk production company wait to be paid for their work.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> But in Laos, Beijing has faced very little resistance. That is in part because Laos, like China, is ruled by an authoritarian communist regime that can act quickly without much scrutiny—and also because its development needs are enormous and China was the only game in town. The country of 7.4 million—with a small workforce and few natural resources—has been of little interest to investors from the West and Japan, which don&#39;t share China&#39;s strategic imperative here.</p><p> It helps China&#39;s case that the train is popular in Laos. Dangerous 12-hour bus rides through mountain roads can now be made in less than four hours by rail, for about the same price. Students and migrant workers can easily visit their families. One couple said they were taking their baby to a hospital in the capital to see a pediatric specialist that their rural province doesn&#39;t have.</p><p> More than 2,000 products are now approved for export via the cargo route, the Laos-China Railway Company said. Fruits such as watermelon and durian, cassava flour, rubber and iron are among the products making their way to China. Mechanical equipment, chemical fertilizers, appliances and solar panels are pouring into Laos.</p><p> When the train launched, Chinese leader Xi Jinping and Lao President Thongloun Sisoulith said the project would bring prosperity to both sides. Just as North America&#39;s first transcontinental railroad created boomtowns across the countryside, Xi promised a “golden route” from which development would spring. Stations were built a few miles outside of towns to make room for urban expansion, with warehouses erected alongside to process cargo. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818982?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Chinese investment follows the train,&#39; said He Ming Jia, a senior executive at Yunnan Haicheng Industrial Group.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Chinese firms are snapping up nearby properties to set up farms and factories. About a 30-minute drive from Muang Xai, a town with one of the train&#39;s major stations, the hills are covered with crops bound for the border. Chinese firms have been harvesting on the surrounding land for decades, leasing large plantations to grow bananas, rubber trees, soybeans and cassava—and now they are expanding further.</p><p> At a mulberry farm, women harvest leaves to feed silkworms that are spinning fibers to be woven into fine Chinese fabrics. A new processing plant opened last year for adlay, a grain used in soupy desserts and traditional Chinese medicine.</p><p> Locals have traditionally been subsistence farmers, growing just enough rice and vegetables to feed their families. Saiy Soulivong, 32, said he used to struggle to find shifts on construction sites to earn extra cash. Now he works as a day laborer at a new cluster of warehouses that companies can rent near a train station.</p><p> “We have more options,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817254?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Chinese tourists gave alms to Buddhist monks last month in Luang Prabang, one of the major stops on the Laos-China railroad. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818986?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Workers end their day with dinner at a Chinese restaurant in Boten, Laos.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Laos is no stranger to the influence of foreign powers. Its cities are famous for colonial architecture incorporating French elements. The US scarred its countryside during the Vietnam War, dropping more than two million tons of bombs on communist hide-outs. Unexploded ordnance maimed villagers and slowed development for decades, but Lao society is still largely receptive to American engagement.</p><p> Since cross-border passenger trains launched in April, arrivals from China have surged. On a recent morning in Luang Prabang, a Unesco World Heritage site popular for its ornate temples and natural attractions such as waterfalls, tourists dropped crisp Chinese bank notes as alms for Buddhist monks at a ceremony. Further north, in Boten, the currency is as common as the local Lao kip and signs are printed in both Lao and Mandarin.</p><p> “It&#39;s becoming more like China than like Laos, but it&#39;s good because they build things,” said Noy Keomanychan, a 43-year-old food vendor who commutes from a nearby village to sell grilled meat and squirrel soup to Lao laborers.</p><p> “That&#39;s how it is,” she said, “the Lao people are poor, and the Chinese are rich.”</p><p> Write to Feliz Solomon at <a href="mailto:feliz.solomon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">feliz.solomon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-grand-vision-for-a-vast-rail-network-transforms-a-neighboring-country-17f067cc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-grand-vision-for-a-vast-rail-network-transforms-a-neighboring-country-17f067cc<author><![CDATA[Feliz Solomon]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>重型建筑</category><category>Railway Construction</category><category> Rail Transport</category><category> Construction</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>Land Transport</category><category> Transportation/Logistics</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Economic Zones</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>economic zones</category><category>重型建筑</category><category>railway construction</category><category> rail transport</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产</category><category>land transport</category><category> transportation</category><category> logistics </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Putin Has Been Humiliated, Put Under Pressure, U.K. Spy Chief Says]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> MI6 head says Russia is now unlikely to regain momentum in Ukraine <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001065877"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5179E0B0-4C30-4FA3-B4FA-848FF823B8D9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fputin-has-been-humiliated-put-under-pressure-u-k-spy-chief-says-894d62c2&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> In a rare public speech on Wednesday, the head of the UK&#39;s spy agency invited Russians who are &#39;silently appalled&#39; by the war in Ukraine to share secrets about the Kremlin with British intelligence services. Photo: Matt Dunham/AP<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001065877"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/max-colchester" itemprop="url" rel="author">马克斯·科尔切斯特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated July 19, 2023 7:13 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/putin-has-been-humiliated-put-under-pressure-u-k-spy-chief-says-894d62c2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> PRAGUE—The head of the UK&#39;s Secret Intelligence Service said Russian President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Vladimir Putin</a> is under pressure as fissures in his inner circle appear and his forces have little chance of regaining <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/blasts-hit-military-base-in-russian-occupied-crimea-c9c1ffc1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">momentum in Ukraine</a> .</p><p> In a rare public speech, Richard Moore, who heads the spy agency known as MI6, said Putin&#39;s offer of clemency to Yevgeny Prigozhin after the mercenary leader&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wagner-prigozhin-putin-mutiny-moscow-march-7072d6ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">march on Moscow</a> was “humiliating” for the Russian leader. Prigozhin appears to still be at large and there are “deep fractures” in the elite circle around Putin, Moore said. Wagner&#39;s operations in Africa <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kremlins-wagner-shake-up-rattles-nerves-in-africa-middle-east-8c917a97?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">appear still to be functioning</a> but the group is no longer active in Ukraine, he said.</p><p> The British intelligence chief said he remained hopeful that Ukraine can gain the upper hand as “there appears now to be little prospect of the Russian forces regaining momentum.”摩尔表示，过去一个月，乌克兰收复的领土比俄罗斯去年夺取的领土还要多，他敦促西方盟友尽可能长时间地武装乌克兰。 Ukraine&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">counteroffensive is progressing slowly</a> in an attempt to keep losses down, he said.</p><p> Moore, who like his predecessors is referred to by the initial “C” and has headed MI6 since 2020, made a public call for Russians to spy on the Kremlin to avoid being on the “wrong side of history.”</p><p> “I invite them to do what others have already done this past 18 months and join hands with us,” he said. “我们的大门永远敞开。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819779?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> MI6 chief Richard Moore says he remains hopeful that Ukraine can gain the upper hand in the war.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Stefan Rousseau/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The spy chief criticized countries backing Russia. He <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/irans-drone-industry-is-getting-harder-to-sanction-500839d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">singled out Iran</a> for selling weapons to Russia for cash.他还谴责非洲独裁政权向俄罗斯雇佣军支付报酬。他询问雇佣兵是否值得信任。 “如果俄罗斯雇佣兵能够背叛普京，他们还会背叛谁？”摩尔说道。 “如果他们向莫斯科挺进，他们还会威胁到哪些其他首都？”</p><p> China remains <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/britain-bulks-up-military-spending-to-counter-russia-and-china-b7c6ca05?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the main priority for MI6</a> and the agency devotes more resources to that country than anywhere else, Moore said. In particular, the spy agency is worried about China&#39;s ability to collect vast amounts of data from around the globe to build highly advanced machine-learning tools and artificial intelligence.他说：“中国受益于巨大的规模。”他补充说，例如，中国迫使各国交出健康数据，以换取中国制造的 Covid-19 疫苗。</p><p> China&#39;s diplomatic ties with Moscow remain firm, Moore said, but the relationship is becoming increasingly lopsided, with the Russian government more subservient to Beijing as the war progresses.</p><p> The reason behind Putin&#39;s decision to cut a deal with Prigozhin to allow him to flee with his life to Belarus was one “even the chief of MI6 finds a bit difficult to interpret,” said Moore. That deal with Prighozin still holds, he said. Putin&#39;s grip on power remains and there doesn&#39;t appear to be any threat to it, but “he has to realize that something is pretty rotten” within the Russian system, he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819782?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Ukrainian soldier sits in a recently captured Russian trench near Bakhmut, eastern Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Libkos/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Moore said spy agencies won&#39;t be displaced by artificial intelligence, arguing that humans can still shape and access information in a way that technology cannot.他说，特别是间谍可以“影响政府或恐怖组织内部的决策”。 “总会有一种非凡的纽带让一个人能够向另一个人倾诉心声，”他说。军情六处未来的作用将是试图揭露那些想要不负责任地使用人工智能的人。</p><p> The decision by “C” to give a public address and take questions from reporters is a new development in and of itself. Until 1992, the UK government formally didn&#39;t recognize that MI6 existed and public utterances by its chiefs were kept to an absolute minimum.</p><p> Now MI6, recognizing that it wants to recruit a more diverse and younger group of operatives, is trying to build a more public profile.</p><p> Britain, along with the US, was also vocal in the lead-up to Russia&#39;s invasion of Ukraine about the threat that Putin presented and that war was likely.</p><p> “I don&#39;t think you need all the resources within MI6 to conclude there are deep fractures within the Russia elite around Putin,” Moore said.</p><p>写信给马克斯·科尔切斯特<a href="mailto:Max.Colchester@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Max.Colchester@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 11:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/putin-has-been-humiliated-put-under-pressure-uk-spy-chief-says-894d62c2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/putin-has-been-humiliated-put-under-pressure-uk-spy-chief-says-894d62c2<author><![CDATA[Max Colchester]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><cat